By Sean Lovullo and Jake Bell

library(spotifyr)

Part I: Introduction

Spotify is one of the largest media streaming services, with over 50 million songs available and over 250 million monthly users. How does Spotify offer song suggestions to its users? It generates data on every song over multiple categories and uses them to find songs to suggest based on what you like. Publicly accessible features include song length, key, mode, time signature, acousticness, danceability, energy, instrumentalness, liveness, loudness, speechiness, valence, and tempo. Pooling data that is publicly available, we want to answer the following question: can we predict the number of streams a Top 200 song on Spotify will get by finding clusters within the data that are based on the given audio features?

To find an answer, we will utilize the K-Means clustering algorithm to cluster the top 200 tracks into groups based on Spotifys audio features. Then we will construct a number multiple regression models; there will be one for each cluster and also one ignoring the clusters. We will train the models using 80% of our data and test the models with the remaining 20% to see how well the model fits new data.

To accomplish these tasks, we will use both R and Python. R will be utilized to generate the data set in real-time, to do much of the data wrangling, and to visualize and model the data. Python (particularly the sci-kit learn package) is used to run the K-Means algorithm to cluster the data, as well as preparing the data to be used in that algorithm.

When using k-means for clustering, we must pick the number of clusters; the algorithm does not tell us what the optimal number is. However, we can make a better decision by comparing inertia values and silhouette scores. The following code generates these values for various values of k.

#test K-means with different cluster sizes (1-8) to find the inertia and silhouette scores
results1 = {}
results2 = {}
for k in range(1,8):
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
  kmeans.fit_predict(subset)
  inertia = kmeans.inertia_
  colName = str(k)
  results1.update({colName: inertia})
  
  if (k > 1):
    s_score = silhouette_score(subset, kmeans.labels_)
    results2.update({colName: s_score})

results1 = pd.DataFrame(
    list(results1.items()),
    columns = ['K','Inertia']
)
results2 = pd.DataFrame(
    list(results2.items()),
    columns = ['K', 'Silhouette Score']
)

For our inertia plot, we are looking for an elbow, or for which value of k the graph bends most. The best point to call an elbow appears to be \(k=3\). Because the elbow is not so clear or defined, lets now look at the silhouette scores and compare those.

#graph silhouette scores to pick the best num of clusters
ax = plt.gca()
results2.plot(x = 'K', y = 'Silhouette Score', kind = 'line', ax = ax)
results2.plot(x = 'K', y = 'Silhouette Score', kind = 'scatter', ax = ax)
ax.get_legend().remove()
plt.title("Silhouette Score")
#plt.show()

We are looking for the highest value for our silhouette score. We can see that our highest value is when \(k=3\). Thus, based on our evidence, we will choose \(k=3\) when we run the k-means clustering algorithm.

#run KMeans algorithm, picking num. clusters = 3, since it is a good elbow for inertia graph
k = 3
init_pos = np.array([
  [-1.414612,-1.175720,-1.155611,-0.691465,0.233730],
  [0.493033,0.298614,0.162068,0.089535,-1.151339],
  [0.139266,0.208380,0.314348,0.194291,0.868554]
])
kmeans= KMeans(n_clusters = k, init=init_pos, n_init=1)
y_pred = kmeans.fit_predict(subset)

Now that we have finished preparing our data, I will restate the focus question: can we predict the number of streams a Top 200 song on Spotify will get by finding clusters within the data? We want to know if we can predict the number of streams a song will get by using the cluster a track belongs to. We will create a model for each cluster, as well as for the whole data set. How should we construct our models? To answer this question, lets examine scatter plots of our predictors with our target, streams.

Section A: Scatter plots

ggplot(data = train_data, mapping = aes(y = Streams, x = danceability, color = cluster)) +

ggplot(data = train_data, mapping = aes(y = Streams, x = mode, color = cluster)) +
  geom_jitter()

Mode is a categorical variable denoting whether a track is in a major (0) or minor (1) key. We intentionally used the geom_jitter object so that all of the data points could be seen. Otherwise, they would all be bunched into tight columns at 0 and 1, and many would not be seen.

We can see that two of the clusters are closely related to this categorical variable, although one cluster seems to be scattered between the two modes. The two categories have a similar shape, having a similar density (number of data points) and height (excluding the obvious outlier for mode 0). Thus, although this was used for clustering, it will not be included in the model, as this categorical variable would clearly not help to indicate the number of streams a track would get.

Section C: Testing the Models

How close are these models predictions of streams to the actual results for new data? We will use our test data sets to answer this question.

Part V: Results and Conclustion

Question: Can we predict the number of streams a Top 200 song on Spotify will get by finding clusters within the data?

Answer: No, we are not able to predict the number of streams such a song would get on Spotify from clusters based on a songs characteristics (as determined by Spotify).

Limitations of Model and Results

  • Only top 200 songs are used, meaning that using the model for a song not in the top 200 would be outside the scope of these models

  • Other more sophisticated regression methods beyond linear regression may yield different results

  • There are other models that can be explored with the given data set

  • Models rely on the quality of the predictors. How accurate are Spotifys track attribute metrics? How are they measured?

  • The k-means algorithm used an initializer for the purpose of keeping results consistent across runs (so that cluster 0 would always be cluster 0 instead of cluster 2, for instance, as such labels are arbitrarily decided). Results vary less than they should because of this.

  • The k-means algorithm was the only clustering algorithm explored. Would another clustering method have yielded better results?

  • Results are based on current data. The consistency of these results cannot be guaranteed over time. Tomorrows data could be predicted either better or worse by these methods.

In Conclusion.

A better data set might be able to answer this question with greater accuracy; however, given this top 200 data set with audio features from Spotify, it appears that we cannot predict the number of streams a song would get on Spotify when utilizing clustering based on Spotifys audio features.
